'''Brady Beeson''' (born February 17, 1987) is an [[American people|American]] [[American football|football]] [[placekicker]] for the [[Spokane Empire]] of the [[Indoor Football League]] (IFL).

==Early life==
He grew up playing [[hockey]], cross-country skiing, soccer, and track and field. He graduated from [[Apple Valley High School (Minnesota)|Apple Valley High School]] in [[Apple Valley, Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.ecmpublishers.info/static/TWL/2005/january/7nordic.html |title=Panther nordic skiers considered the favorites |first=Todd |last=Abeln |date=January 7, 2005 |publisher=Thisweek Newspapers |work=www.ecmpublishers.info |accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref>

==College career==
Having never played high school football, Beeson was a walk-on at [[College of Saint Benedict and Saint John's University|St. John's University]], where he was a back-up kicker for 3 seasons under coach John Gagliardi, the winningest college football coach of all time. In 2009, Beeson transferred to the [[University of St. Thomas (Minnesota)|University of St. Thomas]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tommiemedia.com/sports/it%E2%80%99s-the-greatest-small-college-rivalry-in-the-country/ |title='It's the greatest small-college rivalry in the country' |first=Jordan |last=Osterman |date=October 14, 2009 |publisher=TommieMedia |work=www.tommiemedia.com |accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref> and played his final season for Glenn Caruso and the Tommies. While playing at UST, Brady Beeson set three school records – PAT's in a game (9-9), PAT's in a season (58), and points in a season as a kicker (79). It was his only season as a starting kicker.

==Professional career==

===Tri-Cities Fever===
Brady joined the [[Tri-Cities Fever]] in the 2012 season, shortly before the playoffs. In his debut game, Beeson went 4-5 in field goals (52,45,22 and 24 yards), including the game winner. He went on to be the IFL Special Teams Player of the week. In his two and a half seasons with the Fever, Beeson tallied 39 field goals, 120 PAT's and 238 total points. He is the all-time leading scorer among Fever kickers (59 field goals, 165 PAT's and 342 total points).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goifl.com/news/news-archive/1-latest-news/858-week-15-players-of-the-week |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022055329/http://www.goifl.com/news/news-archive/1-latest-news/858-week-15-players-of-the-week |archivedate=2014-10-22 |df= }}</ref>

===Portland Thunder===
On October 10, 2014, Beeson was assigned to the [[Portland Thunder]] of the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/12-sports/256197-125597-thunder-calls-ramirez-answers |title=Thunder calls, Ramirez answers |first=Steve |last=Brandon |date=April 9, 2015 |publisher=Portland Tribune |work=www.portlandtribune.com |accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref>

===Spokane Empire===
Beeson signed with the [[Spokane Empire]] for a single game, where he 6 for 6 on his PATs. He was released the next week. On May 19, 2016, Beeson was re-signed by the Empire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/empire-re-signs-kicker-brady-beeson/n-5145481 |title=Empire Re-Signs Kicker Brady Beeson |date=May 19, 2016 |publisher=OurSports Central |work=www.oursportscentral.com |accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref>

==Off the field==
Brady Beeson is a coach with Husted Kicking, started by former NFL kicker Michael Husted. Beeson, Husted and others on staff work with high school, college and professional specialists around the country helping them improve their skills.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hustedkicking.com/staff/brady_beeson/beeson_index.html |title=Kicking Lessons and Kicking Camps with Kicking Coach Brady Beeson Minneapolis/St. Paul, MN |publisher=Husted Kicking |work=www.hustedkicking.com |accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref>

